subSubSection.paragraph:
Nymph.
Generally similar to the females, but may be different in marking pattern and coloration. Currently it is very difficult to identify 

Eupolyphaga

species based on nymphs. In the last nymphal instar, it’s easy to distinguish the males from the females: 1) the male nymph with four unseparated and distinct wing buds protruded from the lateral ends of mesonotum and metanotum (
Fig. 44 F
), while the female without wing buds; 2) the male nymph with small subgenital plate, paraprocts exposed, two styli present (
Fig. 1 E
), while the female nymph with large subgenital plate, paraprocts exposed, styli missing (

Fig. 
1 I

). The female nymph differs from the mature female mainly by its subgenital plate, the female nymph with subgenital plate apex transverse, not bulged, two paraprocts exposed (

Fig. 
1 I

), while the mature female with large, protruded and bulged subgenital plate, paraprocts hidden (
Fig. 1 J
).
